providers.name: aws
providers.description: Lifecycle management of AWS resources, including  EC2, Lambda, EKS, ECS, VPC, S3, RDS, DynamoDB, and more. This provider is maintained internally by the HashiCorp AWS Provider team.

providers.name: random
providers.description: Supports the use of randomness within Terraform configurations. This is a logical provider, which means that it works entirely within Terraform logic, and does not interact with any other services.

providers.name: null
providers.description: Provides constructs that intentionally do nothing – useful in various situations to help orchestrate tricky behavior or work around limitations.

providers.name: google
providers.description: Lifecycle management of GCP resources, including Compute Engine, Cloud Storage, Cloud SDK, Cloud SQL, GKE, BigQuery, Cloud Functions and more. This provider is collaboratively maintained by the Google Terraform Team at Google and the Terraform team at HashiCorp

providers.name: azurerm
providers.description: Lifecycle management of Microsoft Azure using the Azure Resource Manager APIs. maintained by the Azure team at Microsoft and the Terraform team at HashiCorp

providers.name: template
providers.description: This provider has been archived. Please use the `templatefile` function or the `Cloudinit` provider instead. See documentation for more details.

providers.name: kubernetes
providers.description: Management of all Kubernetes resources, including Deployments, Services, Custom Resources (CRs and CRDs), Policies, Quotas and more.

providers.name: local
providers.description: Used to manage local resources, such as creating files

providers.name: time
providers.description: Used to interact with time-based resources. The provider itself has no configuration options.

providers.name: external
providers.description: A special provider that exists to provide an interface between Terraform and external programs – useful for integrating Terraform with a system for which a first-class provider does not exist.

providers.name: tls
providers.description: Provides utilities for working with Transport Layer Security keys and certificates. It provides resources that allow private keys, certificates and certficate requests to be created as part of a Terraform deployment.

providers.name: vault
providers.description: Allows Terraform to read from, write to, and configure Hashicorp Vault.

providers.name: archive
providers.description: The archive provider exposes resources to manage archive files.

providers.name: helm
providers.description: Manage installed Charts in your Kubernetes cluster, in the same way Helm does, through Terraform

providers.name: azuread
providers.description: Manage users, groups, service principals, and applications in Azure Active Directory using the Microsoft Graph API. This provider is maintained by the Azure providers team at HashiCorp.

providers.name: http
providers.description: Utility provider for interacting with generic HTTP servers as part of a Terraform configuration.

providers.name: cloudinit
providers.description: Exposes the cloudinit_config data source which renders a multipart MIME configuration for use with cloud-init (previously available as the template_cloudinit_config resource in the template provider)

providers.name: kubectl
providers.description: This provider is the best way of managing Kubernetes resources in Terraform, by allowing you to use the thing Kubernetes loves best - yaml!

providers.name: confluent
providers.description: Simplify Apache Kafka Terraform deployment with the Confluent Terraform Provider. Manage Confluent Environments, Kafka Clusters, Kafka Topics, Kafka ACLs, Service Accounts, and more.

providers.name: tfe
providers.description: Provision Terraform Cloud or Terraform Enterprise - with Terraform! Management of organizations, workspaces, teams, variables, run triggers, policy sets, and more. Maintained by the Terraform Cloud team at HashiCorp.

providers.name: oci
providers.description: Interact with the many resources supported by the Oracle Cloud Infrastructure via the OCI provider APIs.

providers.name: dns
providers.description: Supports DNS updates (RFC 2136) and can optionally be configured with secret key based transaction authentication (RFC 2845).

providers.name: consul
providers.description: Exposes resources used to interact with a Consul cluster, such as adding external services or working with the key/value store

providers.name: mongodbatlas
providers.description: Deploy, update, and manage Atlas configurations as code through Terraform

providers.name: elasticstack
providers.description: Configure and manage Elasticstack components such as Elasticsearch, Kibana and more, as code, on Elastic Cloud or on premises.

providers.name: awscc
providers.description: Lifecycle management of AWS resources powered by the AWS Cloud Control API. This provider is fully generated from the available CloudFormation resource definitions and is maintained internally by the HashiCorp AWS Provider team.

providers.name: nomad
providers.description: Exposes resources to interact with a HashiCorp Nomad cluster.

providers.name: coder
providers.description: Coder is a self-hosted remote development platform. Shifting software development from local machines to the cloud. Onboard new developers in minutes, build code on powerful servers—all while keeping source code and data secure and keeping your developers in flow.

providers.name: ec
providers.description: Provision, manage and configure Elastic Stack Deployments as code on Elastic Cloud.

providers.name: hcp
providers.description: HashiCorp Cloud Platform (HCP) is HashiCorp's first-party platform for hosting our products as managed services. HCP includes shared platform functionality like login, access control, and billing, and can be managed via web portal interface or Terraform provider. It primarily serves to enable easily launching and running services like Consul and Vault, which will be deployed into HashiCorp Virtual Networks (HVNs) and connected to your infrastructure resources.

providers.name: boundary
providers.description: Manage Boundary's identity-based access controls for resources provisioned with Terraform. This provider is maintained internally by the HashiCorp Boundary team.

providers.name: unifi
providers.description: Manage the Ubiquiti UniFi Software-Defined Networking (SDN) platform.

providers.name: instaclustr
providers.description: Lifecycle management of Instaclustr managed services including Cassandra, Kafka, Redis, Elasticsearch and more. This provider is maintained by Instaclustr and the open source community.

providers.name: ad
providers.description: An experimental provider that enables management of Active Directory resources like Users, Groups, and Group Policy Objects

providers.name: metal
providers.description: Equinix Metal - Global, Automated Bare Metal Server Provider

providers.name: azurestack
providers.description: Manage resources in Azure Stack via the Azure Resource Manager APIs

providers.name: ansible
providers.description:
Enables execution of community Ansible automation so users can run Ansible playbooks and roles on infrastructure provisioned by Terraform.
This Community provider is maintained by the community and moderated by Red Hat.

providers.name: hcs
providers.description: HashiCorp Consul Service (HCS) on Azure enables your team to provision HashiCorp-managed Consul clusters directly through the Azure Marketplace. As a fully managed service, HCS on Azure lowers the barrier to entry for your organization to securely connect services and route traffic across a mix of Kubernetes/AKS and virtual machine environments - while offloading the operational burden to the experts at HashiCorp. HCS on Azure is the easiest way to implement service mesh and secure service-to-service communication for your AKS clusters.

providers.name: hyperv
providers.description: Interact with the many resources supported by HyperV. The provider needs to be configured with credentials for HyperV API.

providers.name: backstage
providers.description: This provider is deprecated. Please use datolabs-io/backstage instead.
providers.warning: This provider is deprecated. Please use datolabs-io/backstage instead.

providers.name: salesforce
providers.description: Manage Salesforce user administration with HashiCorp Terraform using the new Salesforce provider.

providers.name: astro
providers.description: The official Astro provider to configure and manage your Astro infrastructure through an API.

providers.name: aap
providers.description:
Management of Ansible Automation Platform (AAP) resources to be able to initiate inventory updates, job execution, and complex workflow orchestration.
This provider is maintained internally by Red Hat's Ansible Automation Platform Provider team.

providers.name: tfmigrate
providers.description: The tfmigrate provider exposes resources that support the migration workflows associated with tf-migrate CLI

providers.name: ioriver
providers.description: IO River provides a unified layer of security, traffic control and serverless compute services on top of Edge platforms. This provider includes management of CDN providers, certificates, services, traffic policies, behaviors, WAF, and more. More information: https://www.ioriver.io/

providers.name: timeplus
providers.description: With this Provider, Timeplus customers at any scale can safely accelerate data streaming initiatives in the cloud (public, private, or hybrid) with infrastructure management that is fully automated through code and integrated within continuous delivery workflows. Supported resources are data streams, Apache Kafka sources, materialized views, dashboards, sinks, UDF, and more.

providers.name: microsoft365wp
providers.description: This repository provides a Terraform Provider for Microsoft 365, leveraging the Microsoft Graph API to enable Configuration as Code for Microsoft 365 environments. With this provider, you can automate the provisioning, management, and configuration of Entra, Intune and other aspects of M365.

providers.name: ode
providers.description: The On-Demand Environments provider is used to manage On-Demand z/OS Environments with IBM Test Accelerator for Z
